<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-10-11T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-10-11T17:00:00-05:00" n="808" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d808">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.77/3363: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-10-11T18:00:00-04:00">October 11,
                                1943—6 p.m.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1461. Reference Chinese operation of French Indochina-Yunnan railway
                        (Department’s 1230 and Embassy’s 1777 and 1865). French Committee here has
                        again informally approached Department. It appears that French employees of
                        the railway have been given notice <pb facs="0902" n="892" xml:id="pg_892"/>
                        by the Chinese to vacate railway residences by October 31. In your
                        discretion, you may mention this situation casually to the Foreign Office
                        and express an interest in equitable treatment being accorded the
                        French.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>